Analysis of Crowd Source Data

The data set crowd.csv is from a crowd-sourcing website that enables uses to submit and discuss ideas to improve the product.

Your task is to build a machine classifier to screen through the ideas and identify the good ones, which will be evaluated by product-design teams.

There are 7046 rows in the data set, and each row is an idea that was submitted in the past.

  • The variable y is the dependent variable and equals 1 if the idea was implemented, and 0 if not.

  • You have three types (the 3Cs) of predictor variables:
    • Contributor:
      • (pastaccept) information about the contributor including the number of ideas accepted in the past
      • (commentsC) the number of comments written by the contributor
    • Content: information about the idea itself. I did text mining on the text of the idea itself.
      • (X1-X11) summarize what is in the text (if you are interested, they are latent semantic indices)
      • (age) the age of the idea (how long it has been since it was submitted)
      • (month) the month it was submitted
      • (diversity) how different the idea is from previous ideas (large values means very different from other ideas while small means that it is a small modification of the product)
    • Crowd:
      • (votes) You have the number of people who visited the site and voted for implementing the idea
      • (comments) the number of comments written about the idea
  • Note: Contributor+Content = (pastaccept)+(commentsC) + (X1-X11)+(age)+(month)+(diversity)

  • remove (pastideas)+(votes)+(comments) if only looking at Contributor+Content in the model

Note that the content and contributor variables are available at the time the idea was submitted, but the company must wait, sometimes weeks or months, for the crowd variables. There are three main questions I want you to answer:

  1. How well (in terms of AUC) can you predict y using only the content and con- tributor variables?
  2. How well can you predict y using all three sets of variables?
  3. Which variables are the strongest predictors and how do the relate to y (in terms of shape, e.g., diminishing returns, increasing returns, inverted-U, etc.)?
  • interested in the difference between linear (ridge/lasso) models
  • interested in the fully automated ones (random forests/trees)
  • Use only the training data (train==TRUE) for determining your model
  • report the AUC values for the test set
  • Fill table with the test-set AUC values
  • Use classification rather than regression trees (type factor(y) as the dependent variable)

Ridge (Contributor+Content)

x = model.matrix(y~.-pastideas-votes-comments, crowd)
fit.ridge = glmnet(x[train,], crowd$y[train], family="binomial", alpha=0)
fit.cv.ridge = cv.glmnet(x[train,], crowd$y[train], family="binomial", alpha=0)
plot(fit.ridge, xvar = "lambda")
abline(v=log(fit.cv.ridge$lambda.min))

predict(fit.ridge, x[!train,], s=fit.cv.ridge$lambda.min, type="coef")
